Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, our only pieces are the black pawn on h4 and the black king now positioned at h3. Notice that the pawn’s forward square (h3) is currently occupied by our king, so we must move the king first. However, we must also be careful not to move our king to a square adjacent to the white king on g1 (remember, kings may not occupy adjacent squares).

From h3 the king could consider these adjacent squares:
• g2 – but that's adjacent to white king on g1
• h2 – also adjacent to white king on g1
• g3 – which is safe (not adjacent to white king)
• g4 – also safe.

Moving the king away from h3 will free the square for our pawn to advance on our next turn. Moving to g3 brings our king closer to the center and supports the pawn’s future progress.

Thus, I’ll make the move: make_move h3g3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, Black has a king on h3 and a pawn on h4 while White’s lone king sits on g1. Here’s our analysis:

• Black’s pawn on h4 cannot advance (the square directly ahead, h3, is occupied by the Black king) and it lacks any diagonal capture opportunities.

• The only moves available come from the Black king on h3. Although a king can step to any adjacent square, we must avoid stepping into squares adjacent to the White king (which controls squares around g1, including g2 and h2). That leaves the Black king with potential moves to g3 or g4.

Between these, moving the king to g3 (UCI “h3g3”) is a logical choice as it steps away from the confines of the h-file and may help activate Black’s forces. 

I will now execute the move:

make_move h3g3
